# Analyze IAB ad templates

**Inputs**: external link to the IAB ad template catalogue (live,
not snapshotted):
https://docs.google.com/document/d/17JXFhHWWX1SVD3s2vMTMO-bvvj9XXK5e

**Output**: `analysis/iab-ad-templates.md`.

**Skip if**: NEVER skip via mtime — this prompt operates against an
external live document that updates independently. Re-run on every
`build-all` invocation. The output MAY become stale between runs;
that is acceptable, and the orchestrator (`build-all.prompt`) is
the one that enforces this no-skip semantics for this step.

---

## Task

Fetch the IAB ad template catalogue from the live link above using
the `WebFetch` tool, or — if accessible — the
`mcp__claude_ai_Google_Drive__read_file_content` MCP tool against
the same Google Doc ID. Extract the list of ad-type templates /
definitions and produce `../analysis/iab-ad-templates.md` with:

1. A header citing the source link, the fetch timestamp (ISO 8601,
   UTC), and a note that this file is a live mirror — a snapshot in
   time of the source, regenerated on every build.
2. A table of accepted ad-type values with columns:

   | Name | Category | Visual placement | Typical duration / interaction | Source paragraph / heading |
   |------|----------|------------------|-------------------------------|----------------------------|

   - **Name** — canonical IAB name (verbatim).
   - **Category** — in-stream / out-stream / overlay / interactive
     / etc.
   - **Visual placement** — where on screen (full, l-shape, banner
     bottom, side-by-side, picture-in-picture, …).
   - **Typical duration / interaction** — short note (e.g. "5–30 s,
     skippable after 5 s", "persistent overlay", "user-dismissable").
   - **Source paragraph / heading** — the heading or section in the
     IAB doc where the entry was extracted from, so a reviewer can
     audit the mapping.

3. A "Mapping to norm chapter 3" sub-section showing how each IAB
   ad-type maps to a value that the norm chapter 3 accepts. Layout
   one row per IAB ad-type, with the norm-side identifier the norm
   would carry and a one-line rationale.

4. If the fetch fails (paywall, 403, redirect-only, network error,
   skill / MCP not available), report the failure explicitly at the
   top of the output file and produce an **empty table** with a
   `<!-- TODO: fetch failed — <reason> -->` marker on each column.
   Do NOT invent ad-type values. Do NOT carry over stale rows from
   a previous run if the fetch failed; leave the table empty so the
   downstream build (`build-norm`) sees the failure and falls back
   accordingly (chapter 3 marked TODO).

## Tone

Direct, tabular, no editorial. The norm's chapter 3 consumes this
table verbatim — every row a reviewer sees in chapter 3 traces back
to a row here, which in turn traces back to a paragraph in the IAB
source doc.

## Log header

The agent MUST log on the first line of execution one of:

  `[GROUNDED_BY=iab-live-link]` — fetch from the source link
  succeeded; the table reflects the live IAB content.
  `[GROUNDED_BY=spec-only]` — fetch failed; the file documents the
  failure and produces an empty table per rule 4 above.

Language: English.
